OL,3,CHalf of Britons turned to neighbours
OL,4,Cfor help in past year ` survey
OL,6,FMore than a third (37%) know their
OL,7,Fneighbours by name and regularly stop
OL,8,Fto talk, while nearly one in five
OL,9,F(18%) have been for a coffee or drink
OL,10,Fwith someone on their street in the
OL,11,Fpast year.
OL,13,FAnthropologist Dr Anna Machin said:
OL,14,F"For decades, longer commutes, rigid
OL,15,Fworking patterns and increasing
OL,16,Fdigital convenience reduced our
OL,17,Freliance on the people living closest
OL,18,Fto us.
OL,26,@vD@AOU
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G4/7
OL,2,W/*%+,"-/.!,.!T,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext Page BNat News CNat TV FClean Feed
FL,304,300,200,140,000,100
PN,30305
SC,0005
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F303A1774832614
OL,3,CHalf of Britons turned to neighbours
OL,4,Cfor help in past year ` survey
OL,6,F"The younger generations in particular
OL,7,Fare rediscovering the value of those
OL,8,Fhyperlocal connections.
OL,10,F"As work and daily routines become
OL,11,Fmore flexible and costs rise,
OL,12,Fneighbours are helping one another
OL,13,Fwith childcare, sharing skills, or
OL,14,Fsimply checking in on one another.
OL,16,F"These everyday encounters, what
OL,17,Fsociologists refer to as 'weak ties',
OL,18,Fare deceptively powerful. A smile at
OL,19,Fthe door or a chat at the bins can do
OL,20,Fmore for our sense of belonging than
OL,21,Fwe might ever realise."
OL,26,@nD@AOUrD@AOUxD@AOU}D@WO]
OL,1,W~k4~sj5j5~s1G                    G5/7
